entry.title: Restore SysUI download notifications on ChromeOS Lacros builds.
entry.content:
SysUI download notifications have long existed in ChromeOS but were

disabled in M105 when new in-browser download bubble UX is enabled:



https://crrev.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/3718438



A new downloads integration is in the works to restore SysUI download

notifications when the in-browser download bubble UX is enabled, but it is still a work in progress. Meanwhile, Lacros is rolling out more

broadly and people are noticing the loss of SysUI download

notifications.



This CL re-enables existing SysUI download notifications alongside the

in-browser download bubble UX only until the new downloads integration

is completed at which point SysUI download notifications will be

provided via other means.



Note that this CL also disables auto-open behavior of the in-browser

download bubble UX on download completion in ChromeOS since that would

conflict with SysUI download notifications in vying for the user's

attention.

entry.title: Allow scoped rules from both shadow pseudo-IDs and scoped style/link elements.
entry.content:
The style resolver previously assumed that an element could have styles

from at most one of (a) a shadow pseudo-ID, that is, a pseudo-element

that references a part of the user-agent shadow DOM and (b) a scoped

style or link element in the shadow DOM. This allows both to be

present, so that pseudo-elements can be added for the sub-parts of the

element.



In terms of the CSS cascade, this treats the styles from the user-agent

shadow DOM and the styles from shadow pseudo-IDs as coming from separate

contexts (https://www.w3.org/TR/css-cascade-5/#cascade-context), with

the user-agent shadow DOM being the inner context and the shadow

pseudo-IDs being the outer context. This means that for rules matching

the same elements (a case not exercised yet), rules using the shadow

pseudo-IDs will win for normal rules, and rules in the user-agent shadow

DOM will win for !important rules. (I tested this locally by modifying

the style sheet in the
element's user agent shadow DOM.)

entry.title: [Profile DragDrop] Add reaction to dragover not to miss any dragenter event
entry.content:
This CL fixes two issues:

- Entering a tile will cause it to shift, however the dragging tile can still stay 'within' the shifting tile. In that case we would expect the shifted tile to shift back, however since no new drag enter event is happening, it won't. Solution: Introduce the drag over reaction.

- Shifting tiles that are on the edge of rows, and shifting from different rows can cause unexpected drag enter events. We do not want to trigger drag enter/over at this stage (when a tile is shifting). Solution: introduce the shifting tag and prevent reactions.

entry.title: Disable UseAuthSessionStorage feature by default
entry.content:
AuthSessionStorage does intentionally not allow concurrent access to its

UserContext and crashes if there's already a user of the UserContext it

holds on to. The UseAuthSessionStorage feature replace the dependency of

AuthFactorConfig on QuickUnlockStorage with AuthSessionStorage. However,

AuthFactorConfig still assumes the UserContext ownership model of

QuickUnlockStorage, where the UserContext is always available (for valid

tokens), so there's a mismatch. This led to crash b/296192527, and

b/296195532 might also be related to this.

entry.title: Implement MediaStreamVideoTrack deliverable frames counter.
entry.content:
In preparation for adding a MediaStreamTrack.getStats() API, update the

blink internal guts to count deliverable frames.



A deliverable frame is a frame that "either was delivered to a sink or

would have been delivered to a sink, if one was connected". In other

words, it is a frame that was neither dropped or discarded.



This does not include any frames while the track is muted (in which

case no frames are flowing, so no frames are counted) or disabled (in

which case the source frames are substituted by black frames and we

don't increment the counter).

entry.title: Implement MediaStreamVideoSource frame drop counters.
entry.content:
In preparation for adding a MediaStreamTrack.getStats() API, update the

blink internal guts to count dropped frames.



In this API, frames will either be considered delivered, discarded or

dropped. Delivered frames are those frames that did not result in a

discarded/dropped event and will be added in a follow-up CL.



This CL implements the discarded/dropped counters on

MediaStreamVideoSource, which is a parent class to all video sources.

This means that a) frame drops are counted even if the drop happened

before the frame reached the renderer process, since `OnFrameDropped`

is signalled via MOJO, and b) the frame counters will work regardless

of what type of track this is.

This adds a function

```

bool IsSaveToPhotosAvailableForImageUrl(

const GURL& image_url, ChromeBrowserState* browser_state);

```

which returns whether the Save to Photos entry point can be presented

for a given image URL and browser state.

A new unsynced string pref `kIosSaveToPhotosDefaultGaiaId` is registered

to memorize the Gaia ID of the account selected by the user in the Save

to Photos account picker if they unchecked "Ask every time".

- i/c/b/shared/public/commands/save_image_to_photos_command.mm

- i/c/b/shared/public/commands/save_to_photos_commands.h

SaveToPhotosCommands is the command handler protocol for Save to Photos,

to be implemented by BrowserCoordinator. It contains two commands

```

- (void)saveImageToPhotos:(SaveImageToPhotosCommand*)command;

- (void)stopSaveToPhotos;

```

which respectively start and stop the Save to Photos feature.

`SaveImageToPhotosCommand` stores the data needed to configure the

SaveToPhotosCoordinator before it is started i.e. the image source URL,

its referrer and the web state it comes from.
